observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require:
a.    The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the LGU’s jurisdiction and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Road Network System;
b.    The Property Officer to render a report on Local Road Network at the end of the accounting period, to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete LRNPCs for all roads and its components;
c.    The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
d.    The Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same with the LRNPCs and the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year; and
e.    The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system of the LGU in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:
Employ the HGDG tool for major/flagship programs/projects of the LGU and identify which part of the project cost/expenditure is attributable to the GAD Budget;
Maximize the utilization of the GAD funds through the implementation of GAD related programs and projects in order to attain the objectives for which funds were provided;
Strictly observe the prescribed format in the preparation of the GPB and the timeline in the submission of GAD Accomplishment Report to the Audit Team; and
Capacitate the GAD FPS by allowing them to attend seminars/trainings related to GAD especially on the use of the HGDG Tool.

We reiterated our recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require:

The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the LGU’s jurisdiction and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Road Network System;

The Property Officer to render a report on Local Road Network at the end of the accounting period, to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete LRNPCs for all roads and its components;

The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

The Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same with the LRNPCs and the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year; and

The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system of the LGU in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that:

The Municipal Accountant adopt the perpetual inventory method in the recording and accounting for inventory items;

The Heads of concerned offices ensure that the RIS is prepared for each requisition of inventory or supply from stock; 

The Property Officer prepare the monthly SSMI to summarize the RIS issued during the period, and submit to the Municipal Accountant, including copies of the RIS, within five days after the end of the month for recording;

The Municipal Accountant prepare the journal entries to record the expenditures or the cost of various supplies and materials issued to end-users based on the respective SSMIs; 

The Local Chief Executive require the semestral physical count of the inventory of supplies and materials, the RPCI of which to be submitted to the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; and

The Property Officer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the RPCI and their respective records, in case of discrepancies, and take up the necessary adjustments.

We recommended that Management:

Require the concerned Accountable Officer to submit the accounts and financial reports to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to the timelines of the abovementioned existing law, rules and regulations; 

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Accounting Office all the disbursements vouchers and payrolls, official receipts, including the corresponding reports of each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month or pursuant to the abovementioned pertinent provisions of rules and regulations, as applicable;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the timelines on the recording and submission of accounts to the Auditor, which is within the first ten (10) days of the ensuing month, as required by the abovementioned existing law, rules and regulations; 

Look into the possibility of augmenting the Municipal Accountant’s Office of personnel from other departments, especially during report preparations and/or allowing them to render overtime, subject to availability of funds, in order to submit the accounts and financial reports on the mandated deadlines; and

Initiate the necessary administrative and/or criminal action in case of unjustified failure/refusal to effect compliance with the foregoing requirements by subordinate officials.

